.\" find-dupes - Find and optionally delete duplicate files
.\" Man page for find-dupes
.TH FIND-DUPES 1 "March 2026" "find-dupes 1.1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
find-dupes \- find and optionally delete duplicate files based on content hash
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B find-dupes
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fIDIRECTORY\fR
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B find-dupes
recursively scans a directory for duplicate files by comparing SHA-256
content hashes. Files with identical content are grouped and reported
with their modification timestamps.
.PP
To avoid unnecessary work, the scan uses a three-phase pipeline:
.IP 1. 4
Files are grouped by size. Files with a unique size cannot be
duplicates and are skipped entirely.
.IP 2. 4
Only files sharing a size are hashed with \fBsha256sum\fR(1).
Files with identical hashes are grouped as duplicates.
.IP 3. 4
Hard links (same device and inode) within a group are collapsed,
preventing false positives.
.PP
When deleting, the oldest file (by modification time) in each
duplicate group is preserved and all others are removed.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-e ", " \-\-extensions " " \fIEXT\fR
Comma-separated list of file extensions to check (default: \fB.txt,.md\fR).
Extensions may be specified with or without a leading dot.
Use \fB"*"\fR to match all files regardless of extension.
.TP
.BR \-d ", " \-\-delete
Delete duplicate files, keeping the oldest in each group.
Without \fB\-f\fR, prompts for confirmation before each group.
.TP
.BR \-f ", " \-\-force
Skip confirmation prompts when deleting. Implies unattended operation.
Must be combined with \fB\-d\fR to have any effect.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Enable verbose output (default).
.TP
.BR \-q ", " \-\-quiet
Suppress informational messages. Duplicate group listings and
deletion output are still shown.
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-version
Print version information and exit.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print help message and exit.
.PP
Short options can be bundled: \fB\-df\fR is equivalent to \fB\-d \-f\fR.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success (duplicates found or not).
.TP
.B 2
Usage error (missing directory argument).
.TP
.B 3
Specified directory does not exist.
.TP
.B 13
Specified directory is not readable.
.TP
.B 22
Invalid command-line option or argument.
.SH EXAMPLES
Find duplicate text and markdown files (default):
.PP
.RS
.B find-dupes /path/to/dir
.RE
.PP
Find duplicate images:
.PP
.RS
.B find-dupes /path/to/dir -e ".jpg,.png,.gif"
.RE
.PP
Scan all file types:
.PP
.RS
.B find-dupes /path/to/dir -e "*"
.RE
.PP
Delete duplicates with confirmation prompt:
.PP
.RS
.B find-dupes /path/to/dir -d
.RE
.PP
Delete duplicates without asking:
.PP
.RS
.B find-dupes /path/to/dir -df
.RE
.PP
Quietly check for duplicates (output only if found):
.PP
.RS
.B find-dupes /path/to/dir -q
.RE
.SH NOTES
Filenames containing backslash characters are handled correctly.
The \fBsha256sum\fR(1) escape format (backslash-prefixed output lines)
is detected and unescaped during parsing.
.PP
Hard links are identified by comparing device:inode pairs via
\fBstat\fR(1). Two hard links to the same file are not reported as
duplicates, and neither is deleted.
.PP
Filenames containing literal newline characters are not supported.
.SH SEE ALSO
